  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is a **felony** in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves knowingly engaging in financial transactions to conceal the origin, ownership, or control of illegally obtained funds. It is a serious crime because it facilitates other illegal activities, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and organized crime.\n\n### Legal Consequences in the U.S.\nUnder U.S. federal law, money laundering is punishable under several statutes, including the **Bank Secrecy Act** (BSA) and the **Money Laundering Control Act** (MLCA). Penalties for money laundering can include:\n- **Prison sentences** of up to 20 years per offense.\n- **Fines** of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds (whichever is greater).\n- Forfeiture of assets involved in or derived from the laundering scheme.\n\nState laws may also impose additional penalties, which vary depending on the jurisdiction.\n\n### International Context\nMoney laundering is also criminalized internationally, with many countries adopting anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations. Organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** work to set global standards and combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nIf you are involved in money laundering, it is essential to seek **legal counsel** immediately to understand your rights and potential defenses.",
